# Senior NestJS Core Concepts — Interview Prep
NestJS is a backend Node.js framework built around TypeScript, decorators, dependency injection, modular architecture, and clean separation of concerns.
Request lifecycle:
Middleware → Guards → Interceptors → Pipes → Controller → Service → Interceptors → Exception Filters

Official NestJS docs describe middleware, guards, pipes, interceptors, and filters as request-lifecycle tools used at different points in the request/response flow.  

⸻

1. Modules

Description:
Modules organize related code into feature boundaries.

Use case:
Group users, auth, orders, or payments logic.

@Module({
  imports: [],
  controllers: [UsersController],
  providers: [UsersService],
  exports: [UsersService],
})
export class UsersModule {}

⸻

2. Controllers

Description:
Controllers handle incoming HTTP requests.

Use case:
Expose REST endpoints like /users.

@Controller('users')
export class UsersController {
  constructor(private readonly usersService: UsersService) {}
  @Get()
  findAll() {
    return this.usersService.findAll();
  }
  @Post()
  create(@Body() dto: CreateUserDto) {
    return this.usersService.create(dto);
  }
}

⸻

3. Providers / Services

Description:
Providers contain business logic and are injected with dependency injection.

Use case:
Keep controllers thin.

@Injectable()
export class UsersService {
  private users = [];
  findAll() {
    return this.users;
  }
  create(dto: CreateUserDto) {
    const user = { id: Date.now(), ...dto };
    this.users.push(user);
    return user;
  }
}

